v.name: noseCone
v.author: C. Jenkins
v.title: Aerodynamic Nose Cone
v.description: Aerodynamic, lightweight and mostly non-explosive. As a reminder to all personnel operating nearby, this part is really sharp and it'd probably hurt if you fell on it.

v.name: airbrake1
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: A.I.R.B.R.A.K.E.S
v.description: Research into feasible ways to slow down a plane in mid-air showed that loose hull panels are pretty great as drag-inducing deceleration devices. The discovery led to the invention of the Aerodynamically Integrated Retrograde Braking Robustly Armed Kinetic Extending System (A.I.R.B.R.A.K.E.S.), which is now popular mostly as a cheap alternative to longer runways. C7 Engineers are still trying to come up with a shorter name for such a long acronym.

v.name: airScoop
v.author: NovaSilisko, Porkjet
v.title: XM-G50 Radial Air Intake
v.description: An intake duct version that can be mounted at the sides of a fuselage. Warranty does not cover engine flame-outs or any objects, inanimate or otherwise, sucked in by the intake. Optimized for subsonic flight.

v.name: airlinerCtrlSrf
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Control Surface
v.description: Large conventional control surface.

v.name: airlinerMainWing
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Main Wing
v.description: One of the largest lifting surfaces in production. The internal volume of these is big enough to carry generously sized fuel tanks.

v.name: airlinerTailFin
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: FAT-455 Aeroplane Tail Fin
v.description: Large conventional wing with built-in control surface.

v.name: AdvancedCanard
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Advanced Canard
v.description: Our engineers thought this design looked "high tech" and therefore must be clear improvement on earlier models.

v.name: CanardController
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Standard Canard
v.description: Our engineers had a stroke of inspiration after "visiting" the Kerlington production facilities. Introducing our new controllable canards. Warning, hard maneuvering may cause unintended stage separation.

v.name: sweptWing
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Swept Wings
v.description: A prototype swept back wing, part of our "Let's Fly", line. Made of light weight composite materials. Guaranteed to generate lift, not guaranteed to ensure crew safety.

v.name: tailfin
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Tail Fin
v.description: This tailfin has passed extensive modeling in our patented P.A.S system.(Paper Airplane Simulation). This fin has been blunted to prevent accidental dismemberment of installing technicians.

v.name: basicFin
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Basic Fin
v.manufacturer: Jebediah Kerman's Junkyard and Spacecraft Parts Co
v.description: This simple bolt-on aluminum fin may not be the cutting edge of aerospace engineering but it's dirt cheap and will make your rocket slightly less unstable.

v.name: CircularIntake
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Circular Intake
v.description: A proper turbofan intake, not only provides oxygen to air breathing engines, it pulls in twice as much air than those puny air scoops from Vac-Co. Optimized for subsonic flight.

v.name: shockConeIntake
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Shock Cone Intake
v.description: A shocking new intake from the C7 Aerospace Division that brought you much adored parts such as the Delta Wing and the Standard Nosecone! Offers exceptional performance at all speeds and has some heat shielding of its own.

v.name: avionicsNoseCone
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: CH-J3 Fly-By-Wire Avionics Hub
v.description: Have you ever wanted to impress your peers by showing off your elite flying skills, but lacked the skills to become a trained pilot? C7 Aerospace's Fly-By-Wire Avionics Hub is the solution! This module allows even the most minimally trained crew to fly like an Ace! WARNING: This module cannot operate autonomously. Warranty void if attempting to do so. WARNING: Module contains no internal gyroscopes or control systems (control actuators sold separately). WARNING: Warranty void without proper use of C7 Aerospace Brand Sickness Bags (sold separately, currently out of stock).

v.name: pointyNoseConeA
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Advanced Nose Cone - Type A
v.description: Less drag due to pointy shape.

v.name: pointyNoseConeB
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Advanced Nose Cone - Type B
v.description: Useful for boosters - the slanted shape is good for leading pressure away from the core stages.

v.name: noseConeAdapter
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: NCS Adapter
v.description: The base of C7 Aerospace's Nose Cone system (NCS)

v.name: standardNoseCone
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Small Nose Cone
v.description: An aerodynamic nose cap.

v.name: airplaneTail
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Tail Connector A
v.description: A simple aerodynamic tail for aircraft. Designed to fit onto all standard 1.25m attachments, this part is the embodiment of our "Let's Fly", line of parts.

v.name: airplaneTailB
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Tail Connector B
v.description: This raised variant of our popular airplane tail provides a lot of ground clearance during take-off.

v.name: fairingSize1
v.author: HarvesteR
v.title: AE-FF1 Airstream Protective Shell (1.25m)
v.description: While the Kerbals at Mission Control were still figuring out how to get their rockets back down to Kerbin safely, the research engineers at FLOOYD were quickly realising that protecting parts on ascent was just as important. Heavy research into two-dimensional-input driven procedural construction was then funded with the hopes of making protective shells for important payloads and interstage areas of the crafts. The protective shells also have the benefit of making the craft more aerodynamic, hopefully saving on precious rocket fuel! The AE-FF1 is the smallest size available from FLOOYD.

v.name: HeatShield0
v.author: RoverDude
v.title: Heat Shield (0.625m)
v.description: A tiny structural heat shield

v.name: HeatShield1
v.author: RoverDude
v.title: Heat Shield (1.25m)
v.description: A small structural heat shield with an integrated fairing

v.name: HeatShield2
v.author: RoverDude
v.title: Heat Shield (2.5m)
v.description: A medium structural heat shield with an integrated fairing

v.name: HeatShield3
v.author: RoverDude
v.title: Heat Shield (3.75m)
v.description: A large structural heat shield with an integrated fairing

v.name: InflatableHeatShield
v.author: RoverDude
v.title: Heat Shield (10m)
v.description: Based on the design of a child's toy, this heat shield uses a set of inflatable rings covered with a thermal blanket to provide a generous 10 meter heat shield for reentry and deceleration, and the aerodynamic qualities of an untethered bouncy castle.

v.name: IntakeRadialLong
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Adjustable Ramp Intake (Radial)
v.description: This intake addresses those sometimes absurd contraptions that SSTO engineers designed in an attempt to pump more and more air into their engines. Optimized for supersonic flight.

v.name: miniIntake
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Small Circular Intake
v.description: A must-have for air breathing engines, this intake duct will pull in outside air to run turbine engines on, as long as there is any outside air to begin with, of course. Optimized for subsonic flight.

v.name: rocketNoseCone
v.author: NovaSilisko
v.title: Protective Rocket Nose Cone Mk7
v.description: A large nose cone for covering up exposed areas of big rockets.

v.name: ramAirIntake
v.author: C. Jenkins, Porkjet
v.title: Adjustable Ramp Intake
v.description: At supersonic speeds, -PATENT PENDING, CLASSIFIED INFO- inside the intake duct deflect the incoming air stream, causing -PATENT PENDING, CLASSIFIED INFO-, which creates a -PATENT PENDING, CLASSIFIED INFO-, thereby greatly increasing the efficiency of this unit at supersonic speeds. Patents Pending.

v.title: Big-S Delta Wing
v.description: The Big-S line of wings are C7's largest lifting surfaces to date. Not only are they Sturdy and heat resistant enough to survive reentry, but also have enough internal volume to carry optional fuel tanks.

v.name: R8winglet
v.author: NovaSilisko
v.title: AV-R8 Winglet
v.manufacturer: Kerlington Model Rockets and Paper Products Inc
v.description: The R8 Active Control Winglet series marked the debut of Kerlington Model Rockets in the Spacecraft engineering world. These winglets are equipped with movable pivots, which allow them to swivel and act as control surfaces. This feature was considered a huge advancement in control technology and most agree that it made Kerlington staff and R8 fans simply unbearable to be around.

v.name: winglet
v.author: HarvesteR
v.title: AV-T1 Winglet
v.description: Nothing is really known about this thing. Use it at your own risk.

v.name: winglet3
v.author: NovaSilisko
v.title: Delta-Deluxe Winglet
v.manufacturer: Kerlington Model Rockets and Paper Products Inc
v.description: The Delta-Deluxe Winglet is a large aerodynamic surface with a small built-in aileron. It is very lightweight and offers more lift than the AV-R8 but the small control surface area means it is not as quick to turn.

v.name: deltaWing
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Delta Wing
v.description: Standard Delta configuration wings. These wings provide high lift and a stable center of gravity for your everyday lifting needs.

v.name: delta_small
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Small Delta Wing
v.description: This small delta wing has breezed through extensive stress tests and design revisions, mostly because it wasn't involved in any of those. In any case, it should work as a comparatively reliable lifting surface.

v.name: StandardCtrlSrf
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Elevon 1
v.description: Made from the finest materials at hand, these flight surfaces are guaranteed to operate while attached to the craft. However studies have shown that a lack of atmosphere *may* slightly impede function. No refunds.

v.description: Made from the finest materials at hand, these flight surfaces are guaranteed to operate while attached to the craft. However studies have shown that a lack of atmosphere *may* slightly impede function. No refunds.

v.name: smallCtrlSrf
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Elevon 4
v.description: Feel the need to attach an elevator, rudder or aileron to just about any surface you can get your mitts on? Well this small elevon is for you. Made of mostly new factory parts, it will fit just about anywhere. Just don't expect a huge performance out of such a small part.

v.name: elevon5
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Elevon 5
v.description: Just another one of these elevon things... wait, this one is swept! Wow!

v.name: wingStrake
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Wing Strake
v.description: Strakes are like sideburns for your plane. The girls will fall for you!

v.name: structuralWing
v.author: Porkjet
v.title: Structural Wing Type A
v.description: This wing has been constructed out of surplus wing components. Comes complete with "like new" finish. Intended uses include very large canards, and leading edges of larger delta wings.
